article.description: Jody Conradt's worrying went for naught.
article.headline: Sick Longhorns 'stepped it up' against Sooners
article.story:
LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Jody Conradt's worrying went for naught.

Concerned because some of her players had the stomach flu, the
Texas coach watched her team put together one of its
best offensive performances so far in rolling past Nebraska (No. 25 AP) 
82-59 on Wednesday night.

Freshman Tiffany Jackson led the way with her fifth
double-double, getting 22 points and 11 rebounds in just her second
start.

"This is probably the best complete game we played in some
time," Conradt said. "Even though we weren't at our best health,
we stepped it up."

Texas (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 5 AP) shot 54 percent in a 47-point second half and dominated
the play under the basket with its taller, stronger post players.
Kala Bowers added 19 points for the Longhorns (18-2, 6-1 Big 12),
while Stacy Stephens and Heather Schreiber each scored 17.

The Longhorns outscored Nebraska 42-26 on inside points and kept
the Cornhuskers (14-4, 4-3) from getting into the transition game
that had been so effective in an upset of then-No. 9 Kansas State
on Saturday.

"They were so strong. We were like a gnat in there," Nebraska
coach Connie Yori said. "We were double-teaming and they were
pushing their hand like, `Get away from me little gnat.' That's
what we felt like."

Playing as a ranked team for the first time in more than four
years, Nebraska stayed with Texas for a half. But the Longhorns
began the second half with a 15-3 run to open a 50-31 lead, and
Nebraska never threatened again.

Stephens, still rehabbing after heel surgery last summer, was
8-for-12 and showed some of the post moves that made her such a
force on last year's Final Four team. Stephens got good position
under the basket for close-in shots and even made a jump hook.

Schreiber, who had averaged only eight points in the three
previous games, was 5-for-8 with three 3-pointers. She made two 3s
and a jumper to spark the Longhorns' second-half run, which Jackson
started with two quick baskets inside.

Texas built the lead to 21 points midway through the half and
did not allow the Cornhuskers to get closer than 15 thereafter.

"We knew coming into the game that they'd be double-teaming us
in the post, so all week in practice we worked on kicking it out,"
Schreiber said. "The guards did a good job of relocating on the
perimeter on the kickout passes."

Several of those passes came from Jackson, who led Texas with
five assists. She has been the Longhorns' top reserve this season,
but responded well to starting, getting two baskets and an assist
as Texas jumped to a 10-1 lead.

"I think our guards just opened things up for us inside,"
Jackson said. "They were all shooting very well tonight and that
made it easier for us."

Keasha Cannon-Johnson's 18 points led the Cornhuskers, who lost
at home for the first time this season. Alexa Johnson scored 13
points and Margaret Richards 12.

"It was frustrating that we couldn't seem to get in the groove
offensively," Cannon-Johnson said. "Definitely, they were very
strong and very physical in the paint. We tried some different
things but they kept scoring. It was very frustrating."

Texas built a 29-17 lead on Bowers' 3-pointer with 5:55 left in
the first half, but still couldn't put the scrappy Cornhuskers away
at that point. The Longhorns went four minutes without a basket and
Nebraska twice cut the lead to four points, the second time at
32-28 on Alexa Johnson's two free throws with less than a minute to
play.

But Jackson converted a three-point play on a turnaround shot
just before halftime and Texas carried that momentum after the
break.

Guard Jamie Carey did not start for Texas after injuring her
right knee against Texas A&M on Sunday but ended up playing 18
minutes.
